Here's the complete implementation using the Hexi library's `file_buffer`:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>

std::vector<uint8_t> read_file_data(const std::filesystem::path& file_path, size_t bytes_to_read) {
    // Open file in read mode
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path, hexi::file_buffer::read);

    // Get available data size (don't read more than available)
    size_t available_size = file.size();
    size_t read_size = (bytes_to_read > available_size) ? available_size : bytes_to_read;

    // Read data into vector
    std::vector<uint8_t> data(read_size);
    if (read_size > 0) {
        file.read(data.data(), read_size);
    }

    return data;
}

std::vector<uint8_t> preview_file_data(const std::filesystem::path& file_path, size_t bytes_to_preview) {
    // Open file in read mode
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path, hexi::file_buffer::read);

    // Get current position to restore later
    size_t original_pos = file.tell();

    // Get available data size (don't read more than available)
    size_t available_size = file.size() - original_pos;
    size_t preview_size = (bytes_to_preview > available_size) ? available_size : bytes_to_preview;

    // Read data into vector without advancing pointer
    std::vector<uint8_t> data(preview_size);
    if (preview_size > 0) {
        file.read(data.data(), preview_size);
        // Restore original position
        file.seek(original_pos);
    }

    return data;
}

void write_file_data(const std::filesystem::path& file_path, const std::vector<uint8_t>& data) {
    // Open file in write mode (creates file if it doesn't exist)
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path, hexi::file_buffer::write);

    // Write data to file
    if (!data.empty()) {
        file.write(data.data(), data.size());
    }
}

size_t get_file_size(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    // Open file in read mode and get size
    hexi::file_buffer file(file_path, hexi::file_buffer::read);
    return file.size();
}
```

Key implementation details:

1. **read_file_data**: Opens file in read mode, calculates how much data can actually be read (to avoid reading beyond file size), reads the data into a vector, and returns it.

2. **preview_file_data**: Opens file, saves current position, reads the requested amount of data, then restores the original position so subsequent reads start from the same location.

3. **write_file_data**: Opens file in write mode (which typically creates the file if it doesn't exist), writes the entire data buffer to the file.

4. **get_file_size**: Simply opens the file and returns the size using the file_buffer's `size()` method.

The implementation handles edge cases like empty files, reading more data than available, and ensures proper resource management through RAII (file_buffer automatically closes when it goes out of scope).

